ribe to these rules, using them only as tools to further his philosophical goals. In Part Two, Craig displays the underlying Platonism of Hobbes's thinking. Sure to be controversial, The Platonian Leviathan may nonetheless re-orient the future direction of Hobbes scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPolitical sciencevEarly works to 1800. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aState, The. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268649640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442686496423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442686496.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK